This PR aims to fix a race condition that the resume event could be pushed to the event queue before the cluster status has been updated. In this case, when the event is processed, the controller might still think the cluster is in paused/maintenance mode. [{"sha":"a3a7adb83ea28667714df91ef7e03dbe358330c3","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Turn off enableSyncDefaultUpdates in test renderer (#21319)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/a3a7adb83ea28667714df91ef7e03dbe358330c3"},{"sha":"78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove `flushDiscreteUpdates` from end of event (#21223)

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

This should allow us to remove the logic in the event system that
tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

Since `OP_REQUIRES` macro expands to a `return;` (among other), calling it in a helper function only ends the helper function's execution earlier, but the kernel will still run from start to end. Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

Since `OP_REQUIRES` macro expands to a `return;` (among other), calling it in a helper function only ends the helper function's execution earlier, but the kernel will still run from start to end. Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"5e6a6e7cda1be67976db1761826f6d11c853979b","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Replacing cuda_py_tests with cuda_py_test where applicable

This commit replaces the use of `cuda_py_tests` (plural) with `cuda_py_test`, in cases where the unit-test has only one source file (and hence the singular version will suffice).

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

values, allowing dynamically sensitive values to propagate through the

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"5e6a6e7cda1be67976db1761826f6d11c853979b","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Replacing cuda_py_tests with cuda_py_test where applicable

This commit replaces the use of `cuda_py_tests` (plural) with `cuda_py_test`, in cases where the unit-test has only one source file (and hence the singular version will suffice).

Amongst other things, test targets defined via the plural version do not seem to get the `_gpu` suffix :(

Ideally `cuda_py_tests` should just iterate over the `srcs` list, and call `cuda_py_test` for each source file. But that change probably has much wider implications, and hence not attempting it here.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/5e6a6e7cda1be67976db1761826f6d11c853979b"},{"sha":"9ad1a52a5dc527bb6ee3e54b357ec4bd1e6d0252","author":{"name":"Haoliang Zhang","email":"0ed73abe53b90931ec96009f1753190a42740aac@google.com"},"message":"*Search for op's predecessor by looking the defining op of its input operand, and search for its consumer node by looking at the user of its result. Since in MLIR, the op which defines the input for its consumer op doesn't always appear as the direct prev node in the ilist structure.
*Rename `prev_op` to `producer_op`, and `next_op` to `consumer_op`.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366400109
Change-Id: Ic281c72235f5ed019f11b2ac1a1aaafce7f87718","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/606e8afd4ab34b0c733462b670bb5956641143c6"},{"sha":"cb7f144b577a92d655d8f8c0243219c1dab7dab3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Pull legacy contrib behavior out of ResourceSummaryWriter

This refactors ResourceSummaryWriter to remove the `v2` parameter, which previously controlled whether the behavior reflected `create_summary_writer()`, aka the legacy tf.contrib.summary API, or `create_summary_writer_v2()`, the API exposed in TF 2. Instead, we just split the behavior into two distinct implementations, `_LegacyResourceSummaryWriter` for contrib and `_ResourceSummaryWriter` for TF 2. This makes each implementation simpler to read in advance of further changes to this class hierarchy.

The symbols have been given leading underscores to discourage their direct usage (since users should refer to the `SummaryWriter` interface only), and I've updated `NoopSummaryWriter` to `_NoopSummaryWriter` accordingly.

values, allowing dynamically sensitive values to propagate through the
configuration. We also remove the requirement for non-root module

[{"sha":"43bf3832d5c8e02ff1fcd00411d2bf2165bc90ba","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"core: Loosen output value sensitivity requirement

Non-root module outputs no longer strip sensitivity marks from their
values, allowing dynamically sensitive values to propagate through the
configuration. We also remove the requirement for non-root module
outputs to be defined as sensitive if the value is marked as sensitive.

This avoids a static/dynamic clash when using shared modules that might
unknowingly receive sensitive values via input variables.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"5ac8a2e974772f78ea76cd877ba8f947abfd1922","author":{"name":"Benjamin Kramer","email":"372985a95acf56297de9d779abaaee9bd47b3ed3@google.com"},"message":"[mhlo:linalg] Add support for lowering mhlo.concatenate to Linalg ops.

This uses a indexed linalg.generic, which is rather awkward standalone but
allows fusing into the output of the concatenate and avoid to ever materialize
it in memory. I think this is the only way to get that with the current linalg
stack, fusion across a concatenate would require more infrastructure.

Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too

for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

Async buffer initialization allows a client to create a PjRtBuffer "future" before the client has the data available, and transfer the data into the buffer (enabling the buffer definition event) at a later date.

Raw copy from sub-buffer to host is useful for streaming copies of device data, for example in order to copy a device buffer to another device over the host network.

The interfaces added in this checkin are not yet implemented.

Async buffer initialization allows a client to create a PjRtBuffer "future" before the client has the data available, and transfer the data into the buffer (enabling the buffer definition event) at a later date.

Raw copy from sub-buffer to host is useful for streaming copies of device data, for example in order to copy a device buffer to another device over the host network.

The interfaces added in this checkin are not yet implemented.

Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

Since `OP_REQUIRES` macro expands to a `return;` (among other), calling it in a helper function only ends the helper function's execution earlier, but the kernel will still run from start to end. Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"a63b8ff98710e0595da5fc6c666e72923c9f157c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/a63b8ff98710e0595da5fc6c666e72923c9f157c"}]

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"}]

[{"sha":"3477caeb05251d8c3e7b619d5a4199be751da0a8","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/3477caeb05251d8c3e7b619d5a4199be751da0a8"}]

We don't need this anymore because we flush in a microtask.

tracks nested event dispatches.

I added a test to confirm that nested event dispatches don't triggger
a synchronous flush, like they would if we wrapped them `flushSync`. It
already passed; I added it to prevent a regression.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/78120032d4ca7ee8611d630d7c67e7808885dfe9"},{"sha":"bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` (#21246)

* Warn if `finishedLanes` is empty in commit phase

See #21233 for context.

* Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/bd7f4a013be3ef272a01874532bee71ad861e617"},{"sha":"a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Flip tuple order of useTransition (#20976)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/a632f7de3bd35eaf6d5082054af4da92dd37cf20"}]

being unwrapped. This makes the QDQ inserting more flexible because all the
min/max operands of the tf.FakeQuant* ops have been folded already.

This patch also moves the related rewrites from the prepare_tf file to the
fake_quant_utils.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

Amongst other things, test targets defined via the plural version do not seem to get the `_gpu` suffix :(

Ideally `cuda_py_tests` should just iterate over the `srcs` list, and call `cuda_py_test` for each source file. allows fusing into the output of the concatenate and avoid to ever materialize
it in memory. I think this is the only way to get that with the current linalg

[{"sha":"c8bd181095dbddcb6e9d9725b53d51acea382201","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/c8bd181095dbddcb6e9d9725b53d51acea382201"}]

My personal workflow is to develop against the www-modern release
channel, with the variant flags enabled, because it encompasses the
largest set of features. Then I rely on CI to run the tests against
all the other configurations.

So in practice, I almost always run

```
yarn test -r=www-modern --variant TEST_FILE
```

instead of

```
yarn test TEST_FILE
```

So, I've updated the `yarn test` command to use those options

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"5e6a6e7cda1be67976db1761826f6d11c853979b","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Replacing cuda_py_tests with cuda_py_test where applicable

This commit replaces the use of `cuda_py_tests` (plural) with `cuda_py_test`, in cases where the unit-test has only one source file (and hence the singular version will suffice).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366400109
Change-Id: Ic281c72235f5ed019f11b2ac1a1aaafce7f87718","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/606e8afd4ab34b0c733462b670bb5956641143c6"},{"sha":"cb7f144b577a92d655d8f8c0243219c1dab7dab3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Pull legacy contrib behavior out of ResourceSummaryWriter

This refactors ResourceSummaryWriter to remove the `v2` parameter, which previously controlled whether the behavior reflected `create_summary_writer()`, aka the legacy tf.contrib.summary API, or `create_summary_writer_v2()`, the API exposed in TF 2. Instead, we just split the behavior into two distinct implementations, `_LegacyResourceSummaryWriter` for contrib and `_ResourceSummaryWriter` for TF 2. This makes each implementation simpler to read in advance of further changes to this class hierarchy.

The symbols have been given leading underscores to discourage their direct usage (since users should refer to the `SummaryWriter` interface only), and I've updated `NoopSummaryWriter` to `_NoopSummaryWriter` accordingly.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"}]

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chrisarcand/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"e62979acfeafac3c9e72ad73d8ccea18217e903e","author":{"name":"njucz","email":"5dcd38fb49ba76993dd97b4916b2abf001ae81cc@microsoft.com"},"message":"fix slash issue on windows","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chrisarcand/terraform/commits/e62979acfeafac3c9e72ad73d8ccea18217e903e"},{"sha":"e1b0e3ce920ffa5c2547b13de3ed61908301497f","author":{"name":"Pam Selle","email":"555625045229d9680c84c16b9cc8a03ab86f7db7@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove -module option for taint and untaint

[{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]

[{"sha":"cb7f144b577a92d655d8f8c0243219c1dab7dab3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Pull legacy contrib behavior out of ResourceSummaryWriter

This refactors ResourceSummaryWriter to remove the `v2` parameter, which previously controlled whether the behavior reflected `create_summary_writer()`, aka the legacy tf.contrib.summary API, or `create_summary_writer_v2()`, the API exposed in TF 2. Instead, we just split the behavior into two distinct implementations, `_LegacyResourceSummaryWriter` for contrib and `_ResourceSummaryWriter` for TF 2. This makes each implementation simpler to read in advance of further changes to this class hierarchy.

The symbols have been given leading underscores to discourage their direct usage (since users should refer to the `SummaryWriter` interface only), and I've updated `NoopSummaryWriter` to `_NoopSummaryWriter` accordingly.

[{"sha":"ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Use performConcurrentWorkOnRoot for "sync default" (#21322)

Instead of `performSyncWorkOnRoot`.

The conceptual model is that the only difference between sync default
updates (in React 18) and concurrent default updates (in a future major
release) is time slicing. All other behavior should be the same
(i.e. the stuff in `finishConcurrentRender`).

Given this, I think it makes more sense to model the implementation this
way, too. This exposed a quirk in the previous implementation where
non-sync work was sometimes mistaken for sync work and flushed too
early. In the new implementation, `performSyncWorkOnRoot` is only used
for truly synchronous renders (i.e. `SyncLane`), which should make these
mistakes less common.

Fixes most of the tests marked with TODOs from #21072.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/ef37d55b68ddc45d465b84ea2ce30e8328297b2d"},{"sha":"89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Continuous updates should interrupt transitions (#21323)

Even when updates are sync by default.

Discovered this quirk while working on #21322. Previously, when sync
default updates are enabled, continuous updates are treated like
default updates. We implemented this by assigning DefaultLane to
continous updates. However, an unintended consequence of that approach
is that continuous updates would no longer interrupt transitions,
because default updates are not supposed to interrupt transitions.

To fix this, I changed the implementation to always assign separate
lanes for default and continuous updates. Then I entangle the
lanes together.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/89847bf6e6c0b77ced5dfc7b794c730bb3deac36"},{"sha":"a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates (#21229)

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/a1558600183b4321d4cdc117925980f1865641fa"}]
